## Anti-patterns to refuse

These are common impulses that this rule exists to push back on. When you feel one of these, stop and re-read the relevant section.

### "This file is over N lines, I should split it."

No. See Rule 1. Splits are triggered by data structures, not line counts.

### "Let me organize this project by `/types`, `/services`, `/handlers`, `/utils`."

No. See Rule 1. Organize by domain entity. A `Book` module contains the `Book` type, its constructors, its operations, and the handlers that consume it. Splitting a feature across four folders by technical role guarantees that every change touches four folders.

### "Both screens have a checkbox list, let me extract a generic `<CheckboxList>`."

Probably no. See Rule 3. Shared _surface_ (a list of checkboxes) almost never implies shared _structure_. The settings panel has a fixed-shape record; the fruit picker has a dynamic list with a size invariant. These have nothing in common except seven lines of JSX. Extracting a shared component forces both screens to compromise their data design to fit the abstraction.

Share the leaf primitive (a single `<Checkbox>`) if it has consistent styling. Do not share the list-level component.

### "Let me make this reusable / generic / parameterized."

Ask: how many call sites are there _right now_? If the answer is one, do not generalize. If the answer is two, look at whether they will actually evolve together. Generalization for an imagined second caller almost always picks the wrong axis of variation and has to be undone when the real second caller arrives.

### "I'll add a getter just in case someone needs it later."

No. See Rule 6. You do not know what shape the future need will have. Adding speculative exports locks in implementation details that you then cannot change. Wait until a real caller appears and then add exactly what they need.

### "I'll define this type with all optional fields so it's flexible."

Probably no. See Rule 4. Optional fields with hidden dependencies between them are the classic illegal-states-representable trap. Reach for a tagged enum first; only fall back to optional fields when the fields are genuinely, mutually independent.

